<tr>
<td colspan="2" style="text-align:center;">
<div class="noprint plainlinksneverexpand navbar" style="background:none; padding:0; font-weight:normal;; font-size:xx-small;">This box: <a href="/wiki/Template:IPstack" title="Template:IPstack"><span title="View this template" style="">view</span></a>&#160;<span style="font-size:80%;">•</span>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Template_talk:IPstack" title="Template talk:IPstack"><span title="Discussion about this template" style="">talk</span></a>&#160;<span style="font-size:80%;">•</span>&#160;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:IPstack&amp;action=edit" class="external text" title="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:IPstack&amp;action=edit" rel="nofollow"><span title="Edit this template" style=";">edit</span></a></div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Open Shortest Path First</b> (<b>OSPF</b>) is a <a href="/wiki/Adaptive_routing" title="Adaptive routing">dynamic</a> <a href="/wiki/Routing_protocol" title="Routing protocol">routing protocol</a> for use in <a href="/wiki/Internet_Protocol" title="Internet Protocol">Internet Protocol</a> (IP) networks. Specifically, it is a <a href="/wiki/Link-state_routing_protocol" title="Link-state routing protocol">link-state routing protocol</a> and falls into the group of <a href="/wiki/Interior_gateway_protocol" title="Interior gateway protocol">interior gateway protocols</a>, operating within an <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_system_(Internet)" title="Autonomous system (Internet)">autonomous system</a> (AS). It is defined as OSPF Version 2 in <a href="http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2328" class="external" title="http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2328">RFC 2328</a> (1998) for <a href="/wiki/IPv4" title="IPv4">IPv4</a><sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>. The updates for <a href="/wiki/IPv6" title="IPv6">IPv6</a> are specified as OSPF Version 3 in <a href="http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5340" class="external" title="http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5340">RFC 5340</a> (2008)<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>.</p>
<p>OSPF is perhaps the most widely-used <a href="/wiki/Interior_gateway_protocol" title="Interior gateway protocol">interior gateway protocol</a> (IGP) in large enterprise networks; <a href="/wiki/IS-IS" title="IS-IS">IS-IS</a>, another <a href="/wiki/Link-state_routing_protocol" title="Link-state routing protocol">link-state routing protocol</a>, is more common in large service provider networks. The most widely-used <i><a href="/wiki/Exterior_gateway_protocol" title="Exterior gateway protocol" class="mw-redirect">exterior gateway protocol</a></i> (<i>EGP</i>) is <a href="/wiki/Border_Gateway_Protocol" title="Border Gateway Protocol">BGP</a>.</p>
